372
00:16:53,931 --> 00:16:57,867
What about, um,
that guy that spits acid?

373
00:16:57,935 --> 00:17:00,002
Bazevich?

374
00:17:00,070 --> 00:17:01,771
He's badass, scary as hell.

375
00:17:01,838 --> 00:17:03,205
Okay, pay attention.

376
00:17:11,282 --> 00:17:12,549
So you kickbox too?

377
00:17:12,617 --> 00:17:14,384
No, never have.

378
00:17:14,452 --> 00:17:16,019
Yeah, but you just can't
pick that up right away.

379
00:17:16,087 --> 00:17:18,622
I'm a quick study.

380
00:17:18,690 --> 00:17:21,092
Ahh.
You're an Alpha.

381
00:17:21,159 --> 00:17:22,660
So are we done chatting?

382
00:17:22,728 --> 00:17:24,562
We got a lot of work to do.

383
00:17:26,065 --> 00:17:28,266
Hi.

384
00:17:28,333 --> 00:17:30,434
Um...

385
00:17:30,502 --> 00:17:32,970
so I raided the soap aisle.

386
00:17:37,610 --> 00:17:39,110
I figured
while we're on stakeout,

387
00:17:39,178 --> 00:17:42,413
you should get to at least
choose how I smell...

388
00:17:42,481 --> 00:17:44,615
which really sounded
a whole lot better in my head.

389
00:17:44,683 --> 00:17:46,650
So you actually went
and bought all of these things?

390
00:17:46,718 --> 00:17:48,719
Yeah, I mean,
I thought about unscented,

391
00:17:48,787 --> 00:17:50,955
but I figure nothing's
really unscented to you.

392
00:17:51,023 --> 00:17:52,223
You're right!

393
00:17:52,291 --> 00:17:55,427
There is no such thing
as unscented to me.

394
00:17:55,494 --> 00:17:57,996
Tom's of Maine
is probably the mildest.

395
00:17:58,064 --> 00:17:59,764
Okay.

396
00:17:59,832 --> 00:18:01,933
And thank you.

397
00:18:02,001 --> 00:18:05,604
You're welcome.

398
00:18:14,981 --> 00:18:16,515
Is that it?

399
00:18:16,583 --> 00:18:19,218
I'm not gonna amp up
just for practice.

400
00:18:19,285 --> 00:18:20,686
It's not healthy for me.

401
00:18:20,754 --> 00:18:23,155
Well, my bet...
is using your ability

402
00:18:23,223 --> 00:18:24,590
is not your problem.

403
00:18:24,658 --> 00:18:26,426
It's holding back.

404
00:18:26,493 --> 00:18:28,629
You got all this pressure
all the time that's building up.

405
00:18:28,696 --> 00:18:30,030
That's why you get cranky.

406
00:18:30,098 --> 00:18:32,700
You have no idea
what you're talking about.

407
00:18:32,768 --> 00:18:35,703
Stop fighting who you are.

408
00:18:35,771 --> 00:18:37,472
Just let it go, man.

409
00:18:37,540 --> 00:18:40,409
What do you want me to do,
huh--sit on the floor,

410
00:18:40,477 --> 00:18:42,844
burn some incense,
say "om"?

411
00:18:42,912 --> 00:18:45,347
As much as I would like
to see that, no.

412
00:18:46,783 --> 00:18:49,817
Harken, you need to relax.

413
00:18:49,885 --> 00:18:52,320
Just try to listen.

414
00:18:52,387 --> 00:18:55,589
Just trust me.
[Distant heartbeat]

415
00:18:55,657 --> 00:18:58,125
Okay?

416
00:18:58,193 --> 00:19:01,628
There's no reason
to struggle.

417
00:19:01,696 --> 00:19:03,297
There's nothing to control.

418
00:19:03,364 --> 00:19:05,732
[Heartbeat grows louder]

419
00:19:05,800 --> 00:19:08,468
You don't have
to reach for it,

420
00:19:08,536 --> 00:19:09,502
'cause it's part of you.

421
00:19:11,472 --> 00:19:15,842
When you want it,
it'll be there.

422
00:19:33,462 --> 00:19:35,563
Told you.

423
00:19:39,902 --> 00:19:42,170
I never thought we'd have
something so ancient.

424
00:19:42,238 --> 00:19:45,874
Dr. Harrison's files were
right there in the archives.

425
00:19:45,942 --> 00:19:47,776
This must be my lucky day.

426
00:20:05,996 --> 00:20:11,600
"It was two years ago,
the 22 of October, 1862,

427
00:20:11,668 --> 00:20:13,301
"it was only my fourth week

428
00:20:13,369 --> 00:20:16,605
"serving with General Wood's
Army of the Cumberland,

429
00:20:16,672 --> 00:20:19,908
but I had already seen hundreds
of men killed in battle."

430
00:20:19,976 --> 00:20:22,077
Shot in the head.

431
00:20:22,144 --> 00:20:25,447
There's nothing we can do
for this poor soul.

432
00:20:25,514 --> 00:20:28,383
"Hundreds more
maimed irreparably.

433
00:20:28,451 --> 00:20:30,552
Can you hear me, son?
His artery is shredded--

434
00:20:30,619 --> 00:20:33,988
- "none of that prepared me
for meeting Jacob Dunham."

435
00:20:34,056 --> 00:20:36,624
[Gasps]

436
00:20:41,564 --> 00:20:43,798
[Knock at door]

437
00:20:43,866 --> 00:20:45,500
- Hey, Cameron.
- Hey, Doc.

438
00:20:45,568 --> 00:20:47,669
Um, are you busy?
'Cause I can come back.

439
00:20:47,737 --> 00:20:49,437
- No, I'm--I'm--
- You know what?

440
00:20:49,505 --> 00:20:51,406
Don't worry. I'll come back.
No, no, of course not.

441
00:20:51,473 --> 00:20:53,674
Come on in.

442
00:20:55,911 --> 00:20:58,946
Wow.
Did you, uh, rob a library?

443
00:20:59,014 --> 00:21:00,648
Looks that way,
doesn't it?

444
00:21:00,716 --> 00:21:02,383
They're Civil War documents.

445
00:21:02,451 --> 00:21:05,453
Right now I'm reading
a physician's war diary.

446
00:21:05,520 --> 00:21:07,154
It's pretty fascinating.

447
00:21:07,222 --> 00:21:08,356
Have a look.

448
00:21:08,424 --> 00:21:12,127
"The journal
of Dr. Zachary Harrison."

449
00:21:12,194 --> 00:21:13,628
Any headaches?

450
00:21:13,696 --> 00:21:15,763
None this week.

451
00:21:15,831 --> 00:21:17,264
You haven't mentioned my name

452
00:21:17,332 --> 00:21:19,567
in any of those records,
have you?

453
00:21:19,634 --> 00:21:22,370
My descriptions
remain anonymous, as we agreed.

454
00:21:22,438 --> 00:21:24,439
You weren't
quite this distrustful

455
00:21:24,507 --> 00:21:25,940
before you survived
that bullet two years ago.

456
00:21:26,008 --> 00:21:27,642
[Chuckles]

457
00:21:29,645 --> 00:21:32,480
Shall we?

458
00:21:41,889 --> 00:21:42,956
[Wincing]

459
00:21:43,023 --> 00:21:44,223
[Gasps]

460
00:21:57,405 --> 00:22:00,974
It's even faster now.

461
00:22:01,041 --> 00:22:04,077
You're getting stronger.

462
00:22:04,144 --> 00:22:08,014
And with no scarring--
simply amazing.

463
00:22:08,082 --> 00:22:10,650
How'd he pull off
that little trick?

464
00:22:10,718 --> 00:22:15,089
By using his Alpha ability.

465
00:22:15,157 --> 00:22:17,592
I think Dunham
is Stanton Parish.

466
00:22:19,729 --> 00:22:22,564
Parish?

467
00:22:22,632 --> 00:22:24,132
You really believe
this guy's been kicking around

468
00:22:24,200 --> 00:22:26,968
for two centuries?
Well, it is hard to fathom.

469
00:22:27,036 --> 00:22:29,004
I-I think this incident
is the first time

470
00:22:29,071 --> 00:22:30,439
he realized
what he's capable of.

471
00:22:30,506 --> 00:22:32,808
How exactly does this
help us catch him now?

472
00:22:32,876 --> 00:22:34,643
Well, learning
about his formative years

473
00:22:34,710 --> 00:22:36,411
might help us understand
what drives the man.

474
00:22:36,479 --> 00:22:39,348
Hmm.

475
00:22:39,416 --> 00:22:41,350
As the old saying goes,

476
00:22:41,418 --> 00:22:44,053
<i>"zhi bi zhi ji</i>
<i>bai zhan bu Dai."</i>

477
00:22:44,120 --> 00:22:46,556
Yeah, that old Chestnut.

478
00:22:46,623 --> 00:22:47,924
That's Sun Tzu.

479
00:22:47,991 --> 00:22:49,625
"Know your enemy
like yourself,

480
00:22:49,693 --> 00:22:53,562
and you may win 100 battles."

481
00:22:53,630 --> 00:22:56,765
So is there something you want
to talk about, Cameron?

482
00:23:01,938 --> 00:23:05,340
You know how much
I respect you, Doc,

483
00:23:05,407 --> 00:23:07,408
and I just--
I wanted to let you know

484
00:23:07,476 --> 00:23:10,678
that, um,
I'm in a relationship--

485
00:23:10,746 --> 00:23:11,846
Dani.

486
00:23:11,914 --> 00:23:14,716
I know.

487
00:23:14,784 --> 00:23:17,686
Well, Nina took it upon herself
to make sure I knew.

488
00:23:17,754 --> 00:23:20,856
- Well, isn't that just perfect?
- Well, I sort of knew already.

489
00:23:20,924 --> 00:23:24,360
I mean, it's--it's obvious,
seeing you two together.

490
00:23:24,428 --> 00:23:27,330
So, as long as you make
my daughter happy,

491
00:23:27,398 --> 00:23:29,032
you can keep your job here.

492
00:23:29,100 --> 00:23:30,667
[Laughs]

493
00:23:33,838 --> 00:23:35,505
[Chuckles]

494
00:23:41,846 --> 00:23:42,980
[Exhales deeply]

